# Pin LF on every file that Linux executes or builds from.
#
# This repository is developed on Windows but runs in Linux containers. A
# checkout with core.autocrlf=true (the Windows default) rewrites these files to
# CRLF, which commits cleanly and only fails later, inside a container, with
# errors that name the wrong culprit. The rules below keep LF regardless of the
# checkout platform.
#
# Scope: .gitattributes governs file CONTENT, not file MODE. The executable bit
# lives in the git index and is unaffected by anything here — a script that is
# exec'd by path needs `git update-index --chmod=+x` in addition to an LF rule.
# (core.filemode is false on Windows, so chmod in the worktree does nothing.)

# bash rejects CRLF scripts and make rejects CRLF recipes. `*.sh` also covers
# services/server/entrypoint.sh, the server image's ENTRYPOINT.
*.sh text eol=lf
Makefile text eol=lf

# The provision starter is a shell script WITHOUT a .sh extension, so the rule
# above misses it. It is copied into the Linux server container and executed,
# where a CRLF shebang becomes "#!/bin/bash\r" (interpreter not found), failing
# with "spawn ./bin/provision ENOENT" and silently skipping provisioning.
services/server/starters/provision text eol=lf

# Patterns without a slash match by basename at any depth, so these two cover
# every services/*/Dockerfile and each .dockerignore beside them. Images build
# on Linux whatever the checkout platform; LF keeps builds identical everywhere.
Dockerfile text eol=lf
.dockerignore text eol=lf
